About the project

Introduction to Open Data Science 2019

I am attending Introduction to Open Data Science (IODS) course fall 2019.

The course helps participants to understand possibilities of open science, open data, and open research tools. Here I will learn to use a few open software tools like R and GitHub, and to visualize and analyze data sets with some fairly advanced statistical methods.

My supervisor recommended this course to me, and I believe it will be very useful for me.

Links

  • My GitHub repository
  • My course diary

About me

I am a MSc in microbiology, I graduated last September. Now I have started my PhD project, where I will study the functions and activity of microbial communities in Arctic and subarctic soils. I work in Jenni Hultmans research group, Arctic Microbial Ecology. Here you can find my TUHAT page.

Exercise 2

# create a plot matrix with ggpairs()
p <- ggpairs(learning2014, mapping = aes(col = gender, alpha = 0.3), lower = list(combo = wrap("facethist", bins = 20)))

# draw the plot
p

Exercise 3

# create a regression model with three explanatory variables
reg_model <- lm(points ~ attitude + stra + age, data = learning2014)

# print out a summary of the model
summary(reg_model)

Exercise 4

By trying different variable combinations in the model, it could be seen that attitude had significant relationship with the points, whenever it was included in the model. In addtion, strategic learning had a significant correlation with the points, when attitude was not included in the model. Age had some correlation with the points. but it was not significant.

# draw diagnostic plots : Residuals vs Fitted values, Normal QQ-plot and Residuals vs Leverage
plot(reg_model, which = c(1,2,5), par(mfrow = c(2,2)))

Week 3: Analysis excercise

R Markdown

This is an R Markdown document. Markdown is a simple formatting syntax for authoring HTML, PDF, and MS Word documents. For more details on using R Markdown see http://rmarkdown.rstudio.com.

When you click the Knit button a document will be generated that includes both content as well as the output of any embedded R code chunks within the document. You can embed an R code chunk like this:

summary(cars)
##      speed           dist       
##  Min.   : 4.0   Min.   :  2.00  
##  1st Qu.:12.0   1st Qu.: 26.00  
##  Median :15.0   Median : 36.00  
##  Mean   :15.4   Mean   : 42.98  
##  3rd Qu.:19.0   3rd Qu.: 56.00  
##  Max.   :25.0   Max.   :120.00
